  "texts": [
    "The curvature of ∇ ad is O'Neill's A-tensor, which we view as an adM -valued 2form on B: for X, Y ∈ T B, A X,Y ∈ Γ(adM) corresponds to the invariant vertical field 1 2 V[ X, Ȳ].",
    "Naturally, A = 0 if and only if H is an integrable distribution.",
    "For each U ∈ Γ(adM), we also set AU to be the (R-valued) 2-form on B given by (X, Y) → h(A X,Y, U).For each X ∈ T B, we denote by L X the shape operator of the fibres in M, viewed as a h-self-adjoint endomorphism of adM.",
    "It is implicitly defined by(13) h(L X U, V) = g(∇ X Û, V).The fibres' mean curvature vector H is the basic horizontal vector field given by the trace of the second fundamental form after raising an index.",
    "The corresponding vector field H on B satisfies g B (H, X) = -tr L X, and is thus given in terms of any orthonormal frame {X j } for B byH = - dim B j=1 (tr L Xj) • X j.The fibre's Ricci curvature is an invariant section of Sym 2 (V *), and it thus corresponds to a section Ric h of Sym 2 (adM) *.Following [Cor88], we also make the following definition:Definition 2.16."
  ],
